docs.abstract: A snippet of the documentary “Rosedale: The Way It Is” has ricocheted across the internet, upending for another generation New York City’s narrative as a bastion of tolerance.
docs.snippet: A snippet of the documentary “Rosedale: The Way It Is” has ricocheted across the internet, upending for another generation New York City’s narrative as a bastion of tolerance.
docs.lead_paragraph: The video rolls on a sunny suburban street, and a group of black children bike toward what looks to them like a parade — there’s a small crowd, and an American flag. Suddenly, they’re swarmed by a group of white children, who hurl racial epithets and rocks. Adults gathered nearby do nothing.

headline.main: A Racist Attack on Children Was Taped in 1975. We Found Them.
headline.print_headline: A Racist Attack Was Caught on Camera. Nearly 45 Years Later, It Still Stings.

docs.abstract: His pregame interview with Sean Hannity offers unfettered airtime in front of a huge national audience.
docs.snippet: His pregame interview with Sean Hannity offers unfettered airtime in front of a huge national audience.
docs.lead_paragraph: Of all the surreal things I’ve seen during Super Bowl telecasts in my lifetime — the wardrobe malfunction, Left Shark, whatever in the world they’re doing to poor Mr. Peanut — I’m not sure anything feels more discordant with the way we live today than the fact that Bill O’Reilly interviewed President Barack Obama before two Super Bowls.

headline.main: For Better or Worse, Trump Will Get His Favorite Things on Super Bowl Sunday
